WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.924 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.924 --> 00:00:03.367 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.367 --> 00:00:04.810 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:04.810 --> 00:00:11.648 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.648 --> 00:00:12.440 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK.

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:17.060 align:middle line:84%
So first, let me look
at a curve and plane.

00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:20.980 align:middle line:84%
Talked a little bit about this
last time at the very end.

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:27.800 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:29.720 align:middle line:90%
Oops.

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:30.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:34.720 align:middle line:84%
So let's first talk about
curves in the plane.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:42.880 align:middle line:84%
So we have functions, f
and g, on some interval,

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:51.480 align:middle line:84%
say, from a to b into R.
And I'm assuming that f

00:00:51.480 --> 00:01:08.410 align:middle line:84%
and g are differentiable
and that the derivative

00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:09.470 align:middle line:90%
are continuous.

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:16.055 align:middle line:90%


00:01:16.055 --> 00:01:18.530 align:middle line:90%
And then I'm thinking about--

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:20.430 align:middle line:84%
so I'm thinking
about the curves.

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:23.230 align:middle line:90%
So gamma here of s is a curve.

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:26.675 align:middle line:90%


00:01:26.675 --> 00:01:32.910 align:middle line:84%
And it's given by the gamma
of s is f of s comma g of s.

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:35.650 align:middle line:90%


00:01:35.650 --> 00:01:38.870 align:middle line:84%
And I want to look at
the length of this curve.

00:01:38.870 --> 00:01:42.790 align:middle line:84%
So s here is running in
the interval from a to b.

00:01:42.790 --> 00:01:45.730 align:middle line:90%


00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:47.490 align:middle line:90%
And so the length--

00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:50.310 align:middle line:84%
and this is the
definition of the length,

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:52.610 align:middle line:90%
but then we will justify it.

00:01:52.610 --> 00:01:59.740 align:middle line:90%
So the length of gamma.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:03.070 align:middle line:90%


00:02:03.070 --> 00:02:08.470 align:middle line:84%
So L is equal to the
integral from a to b

00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:18.430 align:middle line:84%
of square root of f prime of
s squared plus g prime of s

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:22.750 align:middle line:90%
squared ds.

00:02:22.750 --> 00:02:25.230 align:middle line:90%
Now, why is this the case?

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:31.030 align:middle line:84%
So why is this a
sensible definition?

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:38.750 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that this thing
here is f of a comma g of a.

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:43.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is the starting
point of the curve.

00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:46.290 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that the
curve looks like this.

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:48.660 align:middle line:90%
So here is the endpoint.

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:51.550 align:middle line:90%


00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:54.830 align:middle line:84%
And now imagine that
you take the interval

00:02:54.830 --> 00:03:01.320 align:middle line:84%
from a to b and you partition
it into a lot of small--

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:05.840 align:middle line:84%
so you have this partition
of this interval.

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:09.140 align:middle line:90%
And then you're looking at--

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:11.120 align:middle line:90%
so we have the curve here.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:14.520 align:middle line:90%
This is maybe xi minus 1.

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:18.080 align:middle line:90%
And here I have xi.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:24.640 align:middle line:84%
And under the map gamma,
this little interval

00:03:24.640 --> 00:03:29.410 align:middle line:84%
here is mapped maybe into
this piece of the curve.

00:03:29.410 --> 00:03:33.990 align:middle line:90%


00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:37.640 align:middle line:84%
Now, this piece of
the curve, I will then

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:42.240 align:middle line:84%
approximate it by the line
segment from here to here.

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:48.020 align:middle line:84%
So if you do that, then it
means that you are looking at--

00:03:48.020 --> 00:03:51.660 align:middle line:84%
so you have that
you're looking--

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:53.360 align:middle line:90%
so you have that--

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:57.020 align:middle line:90%
so here you have xi minus 1.

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.380 align:middle line:90%
Here you have xi.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:06.500 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking at the
curve on this little interval.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:11.700 align:middle line:90%
And there the curve goes from--

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:17.519 align:middle line:90%
so the initial point is this.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:20.220 align:middle line:90%
That's the image of that point.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And the image of
this is gamma of xi.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:27.060 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:31.670 align:middle line:84%
And so the line segment
from here to here--

00:04:31.670 --> 00:04:34.660 align:middle line:90%


00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:37.300 align:middle line:84%
so the length of
this line segment

00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:40.380 align:middle line:90%
if you have this point here--

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:47.860 align:middle line:84%
so this is gamma of xi minus
1, and this is gamma of xi.

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:54.410 align:middle line:84%
Then the length here
is the vector here.

00:04:54.410 --> 00:05:00.670 align:middle line:84%
So gamma of xi minus
gamma of xi minus 1.

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:02.630 align:middle line:90%
The length of this.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:06.490 align:middle line:90%
But this thing here is--

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:10.110 align:middle line:90%
this is the point.

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:10.630 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:11.130 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:16.070 align:middle line:90%


00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:18.620 align:middle line:90%
And the beginning point is this.

00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:28.150 align:middle line:90%


00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:31.910 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- so it's
the length of this.

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:35.030 align:middle line:84%
But the length of
this by Pythagoras

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:40.450 align:middle line:84%
is the square of
the coordinates.

00:05:40.450 --> 00:05:46.670 align:middle line:90%


00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:49.590 align:middle line:84%
And then taking the
square root of that.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:54.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is what the length
of the line segment here is.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:06:02.680 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:05.880 align:middle line:84%
But now, the mean
value theorem tells you

00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:10.200 align:middle line:84%
that this thing
here is essentially

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:15.060 align:middle line:84%
the derivative at some
point in between these two.

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:18.320 align:middle line:90%


00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:22.280 align:middle line:84%
It actually is equal
to, if you will,

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:27.785 align:middle line:84%
the derivative at some
intermediate point

00:06:27.785 --> 00:06:32.440 align:middle line:84%
times the length of
that little interval.

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.680 align:middle line:90%
This is this difference here.

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:41.240 align:middle line:84%
And likewise-- so
this is x, like this,

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:42.920 align:middle line:90%
some intermediate point.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:48.080 align:middle line:84%
And likewise for this, there's
some intermediate point

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:51.860 align:middle line:90%
times the length here.

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:54.500 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this
little line segment

00:06:54.500 --> 00:07:06.020 align:middle line:84%
here, the length of this little
line segment is equal to--

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:09.700 align:middle line:84%
and you see that when
you take this thing here

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:13.600 align:middle line:84%
and you square it, then
you can factor out.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:15.500 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write it out.

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:17.000 align:middle line:90%
So you take this thing here.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So it's f prime, like this,
squared, delta xi squared plus,

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:37.260 align:middle line:84%
and then g prime squared
delta xi squared.

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.840 align:middle line:90%
But now you can factor this out.

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:48.260 align:middle line:84%
So you can write this as square
root of delta xi squared,

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:55.510 align:middle line:84%
and then f prime, like
this, squared plus g

00:07:55.510 --> 00:08:01.030 align:middle line:84%
prime in this intermediate
point squared.

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:03.470 align:middle line:84%
And this here factors
out both of them.

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:06.890 align:middle line:84%
And so now you can just--
when you take the square root,

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:08.750 align:middle line:90%
it actually goes out as--

00:08:08.750 --> 00:08:10.830 align:middle line:90%
this is anyway positive.

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:12.720 align:middle line:90%
So it becomes like this.

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:17.510 align:middle line:90%


00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:27.430 align:middle line:84%
And now the functions g prime
and f prime are both continuous.

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:30.790 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is roughly what

00:08:30.790 --> 00:08:33.390 align:middle line:90%
it is at one of the endpoints.

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:39.770 align:middle line:84%
So this here is roughly
equal to, like this.

00:08:39.770 --> 00:08:42.110 align:middle line:90%
And then it's like one endpoint.

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:43.930 align:middle line:90%
Or you can even take the--

00:08:43.930 --> 00:08:44.430 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:08:44.430 --> 00:08:45.980 align:middle line:90%
So it's like an endpoint.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:52.650 align:middle line:90%


00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:55.710 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this thing
here now, when you sum up--

00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:58.930 align:middle line:90%


00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:02.690 align:middle line:84%
when you sum up all of
these over this partition

00:09:02.690 --> 00:09:09.770 align:middle line:84%
and you let the partition--
the delta xi goes to 0,

00:09:09.770 --> 00:09:13.890 align:middle line:84%
then this here is going to
converge to the integral

00:09:13.890 --> 00:09:24.010 align:middle line:84%
from a to b of the square root
of f prime of s squared plus g

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:29.790 align:middle line:90%
prime of s squared ds.

00:09:29.790 --> 00:09:31.390 align:middle line:90%
So that's why.

00:09:31.390 --> 00:09:34.130 align:middle line:90%
So you take this little curve.

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:35.310 align:middle line:90%
It's parameterized.

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:37.930 align:middle line:84%
So you take the curve
parameterized by a to b.

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:42.770 align:middle line:90%
You're looking at a partition.

00:09:42.770 --> 00:09:47.420 align:middle line:84%
And then, on each of
these little intervals,

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:53.420 align:middle line:84%
you approximate the curve
by the line segment.

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:57.260 align:middle line:84%
And then you let the-- as
you let this refinement--

00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:03.700 align:middle line:84%
the length of these individual
intervals goes to 0,

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:08.280 align:middle line:84%
then actually this
approximation will have a limit.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:11.200 align:middle line:90%
And that limit is this integral.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:16.820 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we define
it to be the arc length.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:18.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:19.820 align:middle line:90%
So that's arc length.

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:22.330 align:middle line:84%
And so let's look at
an example of this.

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:29.140 align:middle line:90%


00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:31.080 align:middle line:90%
So we'll look at two examples.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:36.500 align:middle line:84%
Let me first look at the case
where f of s is equal to s

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:44.940 align:middle line:84%
and g of s is
equal to s squared.

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:46.380 align:middle line:90%
Then I have that.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:48.440 align:middle line:90%
So then the curve is--

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:54.160 align:middle line:84%
so the curve gamma of
s is s comma s squared.

00:10:54.160 --> 00:11:03.800 align:middle line:84%
And f prime of s is equal to 1
and g prime of s is equal to 2s.

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:06.520 align:middle line:90%
And so this means that--

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:09.040 align:middle line:84%
and let's say that
it's parameterized,

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:13.120 align:middle line:90%
s here, from 0 to 1.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:15.920 align:middle line:84%
So then the length
here of this curve

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:20.800 align:middle line:84%
is the integral from 0 to
1 and then square root.

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:23.780 align:middle line:84%
And then you have to take
this thing here squared.

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:31.040 align:middle line:84%
So that's 1 plus this
here, 2s squared, ds.

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:35.920 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- and it's
this integral here,

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:39.640 align:middle line:90%
1 plus 4s squared.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:41.880 align:middle line:90%
So that's the arc length.

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:44.850 align:middle line:90%
So it's given us this integral.

00:11:44.850 --> 00:11:51.650 align:middle line:84%
The second example I want
to look at for arc length

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:56.670 align:middle line:90%
is if you have the unit circle.

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:58.760 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you
have the unit circle.

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:03.370 align:middle line:90%


00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:06.010 align:middle line:90%
So here you have one.

00:12:06.010 --> 00:12:08.970 align:middle line:84%
So this is supposed
to be the unit circle.

00:12:08.970 --> 00:12:15.510 align:middle line:84%
So it's x squared plus
y squared equal to 1.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:18.020 align:middle line:84%
It's a unit circle
centered at the origin.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:20.610 align:middle line:90%


00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:26.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, this means that
if you take a point,

00:12:26.170 --> 00:12:31.450 align:middle line:84%
then y here is--
so this here means

00:12:31.450 --> 00:12:36.090 align:middle line:84%
that y is given in terms
of x, where that y squared

00:12:36.090 --> 00:12:40.490 align:middle line:90%
is equal to 1 minus x squared.

00:12:40.490 --> 00:12:44.940 align:middle line:84%
And so if you assuming
that you are in this upper,

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:51.300 align:middle line:84%
where y is positive-- so
if y here is positive--

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:55.980 align:middle line:84%
then you're looking at y
equal to square root of 1

00:12:55.980 --> 00:12:58.420 align:middle line:90%
minus x squared.

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:06.500 align:middle line:84%
So in this part here, where y is
positive, you have the curve--

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:12.380 align:middle line:84%
this part here of
the unit circle.

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:16.580 align:middle line:84%
This one here is given
by the parametrization

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:23.140 align:middle line:84%
gamma of s equal to s,
and then square root of 1

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:26.660 align:middle line:90%
minus s squared.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:31.060 align:middle line:90%
And s here is now running--

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:32.600 align:middle line:90%
s is the first coordinate.

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:35.460 align:middle line:90%
So it's between minus 1 and 1.

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:40.900 align:middle line:84%
So s here is between
minus 1 and 1.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:42.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:48.920 align:middle line:84%
Now suppose that you
take some x here.

00:13:48.920 --> 00:13:51.760 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that
you want to look at,

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:55.520 align:middle line:84%
what is the arc length of
this part of the circle?

00:13:55.520 --> 00:14:00.960 align:middle line:84%
Well, then, in this
case, if you're

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:04.020 align:middle line:84%
looking at the arc length
of this part of the circle--

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:10.520 align:middle line:84%
let's call that
arc length theta.

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:15.380 align:middle line:84%
So theta here is
equal to this part.

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:20.040 align:middle line:84%
It's not parameterized
like this.

00:14:20.040 --> 00:14:21.620 align:middle line:90%
But x here is--

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:23.560 align:middle line:90%
so this here is--

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:28.680 align:middle line:90%
so length of gamma.

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:35.640 align:middle line:84%
But now gamma-- by now, s
here is running from x to 1.

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:39.360 align:middle line:84%
Because x is the
first coordinate

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:42.010 align:middle line:90%
and it's running from--

00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:45.970 align:middle line:84%
the first coordinate is running
from x, from this point, this

00:14:45.970 --> 00:14:47.955 align:middle line:90%
here, to 1.

00:14:47.955 --> 00:14:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:14:51.810 --> 00:14:56.690 align:middle line:84%
And so now, let's try to
calculate this length,

00:14:56.690 --> 00:14:59.850 align:middle line:84%
or at least write it
up as an integral.

00:14:59.850 --> 00:15:05.230 align:middle line:84%
So if we write it up as an
integral, we have that--

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:10.010 align:middle line:84%
so in this case-- so gamma
s is equal to s square root

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:13.250 align:middle line:90%
of 1 minus s squared.

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:19.690 align:middle line:84%
And so if we define f of
s equal to s and g of s

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:24.410 align:middle line:84%
equal to square root
of 1 minus s squared,

00:15:24.410 --> 00:15:27.530 align:middle line:90%
then we take f prime--

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:30.610 align:middle line:90%
well, that's equal to 1--

00:15:30.610 --> 00:15:34.150 align:middle line:90%
and g prime.

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:36.530 align:middle line:90%
So then we use the chain rule.

00:15:36.530 --> 00:15:41.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is equal to
1 over 2 square root

00:15:41.910 --> 00:15:43.930 align:middle line:90%
of 1 minus s squared.

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:47.110 align:middle line:84%
And then we have to take
the derivative of this also.

00:15:47.110 --> 00:15:51.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is times
minus 2s, like that.

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:55.270 align:middle line:90%


00:15:55.270 --> 00:15:58.470 align:middle line:84%
And so this here is, of
course, then equal to.

00:15:58.470 --> 00:15:59.990 align:middle line:90%
The 2 cancels.

00:15:59.990 --> 00:16:03.350 align:middle line:84%
And you're getting
minus s over square root

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:04.790 align:middle line:90%
of 1 minus s squared.

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:09.070 align:middle line:90%


00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:12.210 align:middle line:84%
And so now, if
you're looking at--

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:18.290 align:middle line:84%
so f prime squared
plus g prime squared,

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:20.690 align:middle line:90%
this is equal to f is 1.

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:24.390 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1 plus this
thing here squared.

00:16:24.390 --> 00:16:26.590 align:middle line:90%
So this is s squared.

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:30.370 align:middle line:84%
And then the denominator
squared is just, of course,

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:33.670 align:middle line:90%
1 minus s squared.

00:16:33.670 --> 00:16:40.840 align:middle line:84%
And we can now put it
with a common denominator.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:44.600 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
is 1 minus s squared.

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:45.980 align:middle line:90%
1 minus s squared.

00:16:45.980 --> 00:16:48.160 align:middle line:90%
That's how you write 1.

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:52.420 align:middle line:84%
And then plus s squared
1 minus s squared.

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:56.280 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
whole thing is the s squared

00:16:56.280 --> 00:16:59.480 align:middle line:90%
cancel in the denominator.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:03.779 align:middle line:84%
And so you're getting 1
over 1 minus s squared.

00:17:03.779 --> 00:17:06.960 align:middle line:90%


00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:11.599 align:middle line:84%
And so this means
that the integral--

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:13.500 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
the integral--

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:17.720 align:middle line:90%


00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:19.180 align:middle line:90%
so this length here--

00:17:19.180 --> 00:17:22.280 align:middle line:90%


00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.579 align:middle line:90%
and the length is--

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:29.720 align:middle line:84%
so actually, we call
the length theta.

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And it will be clear in
a minute why I do this.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So the length here is then
the integral from x to 1.

00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:45.830 align:middle line:84%
And then it is of
the square root.

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:49.290 align:middle line:84%
So it's supposed to be the
square root of this thing here.

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:51.770 align:middle line:90%
So it's the square root.

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:58.160 align:middle line:84%
So if you will, it's 1 square
root of 1 minus s squared ds.

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:02.050 align:middle line:90%


00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:04.930 align:middle line:90%
So that's the length.

00:18:04.930 --> 00:18:09.050 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about it--
so you have here the unit

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:11.170 align:middle line:90%
circle again.

00:18:11.170 --> 00:18:16.450 align:middle line:84%
What we now calculated was
that we take some x here,

00:18:16.450 --> 00:18:22.330 align:middle line:84%
and then we calculate the
length of this piece here.

00:18:22.330 --> 00:18:24.930 align:middle line:90%
Well, that piece is--

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:27.750 align:middle line:90%
this here is also--

00:18:27.750 --> 00:18:30.050 align:middle line:90%
this is how you define.

00:18:30.050 --> 00:18:31.820 align:middle line:90%
If you will, this is the angle.

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.790 align:middle line:90%


00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:38.310 align:middle line:90%
So theta is the angle.

00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:41.790 align:middle line:90%
And so you see that--

00:18:41.790 --> 00:18:47.510 align:middle line:90%
so theta here is the angle.

00:18:47.510 --> 00:18:52.790 align:middle line:90%
And x here-- x here is--

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:54.190 align:middle line:90%
and this point here--

00:18:54.190 --> 00:19:02.270 align:middle line:84%
sorry, this point here is
cosine to the angle comma

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:04.770 align:middle line:90%
sine to the angle.

00:19:04.770 --> 00:19:06.310 align:middle line:90%
That's this piece.

00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:12.940 align:middle line:84%
So this means that x is actually
cosine through the angle.

00:19:12.940 --> 00:19:20.990 align:middle line:90%


00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:26.550 align:middle line:90%
So this means that theta here--

00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:33.370 align:middle line:84%
in terms of x, theta is
the inverse function.

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So it's what's called
arc cosine to x.

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:45.580 align:middle line:84%
So this arccosine, it means
that it's the inverse function.

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:51.960 align:middle line:84%
If you take the inverse function
on both sides of this then--

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:54.600 align:middle line:84%
so if you take the
inverse function--

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.840 align:middle line:90%
so arccosine.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So you get arccosine
to x on this side.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:05.280 align:middle line:84%
This side, you're getting
arccosine and then

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.600 align:middle line:90%
cosine to theta.

00:20:08.600 --> 00:20:13.400 align:middle line:84%
But these two functions
together gives you the identity.

00:20:13.400 --> 00:20:16.140 align:middle line:90%
So this is just theta.

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:16.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:16.640 --> 00:20:20.160 align:middle line:90%


00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:20.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:28.400 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, what you
have is that arccosine to x

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:33.940 align:middle line:84%
is given as the
integral from x to 1 1

00:20:33.940 --> 00:20:39.000 align:middle line:84%
over square root of
1 minus s squared ds.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:44.200 align:middle line:84%
So you have this formula here,
which is not so surprising.

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:46.780 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, you can
get it from this.

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:50.980 align:middle line:84%
And so now you can get it-- so
now, the fundamental theorem

00:20:50.980 --> 00:20:52.040 align:middle line:90%
of calculus.

00:20:52.040 --> 00:21:09.920 align:middle line:84%
So by the fundamental theorem
of calculus, then you have that.

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:12.380 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
function that is

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:15.340 align:middle line:84%
given like an
integral like this,

00:21:15.340 --> 00:21:20.700 align:middle line:84%
then this thing here
is the derivative.

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:23.200 align:middle line:84%
That's what the fundamental
theorem of calculus say.

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:25.700 align:middle line:84%
Except you have to be a little
bit careful because this

00:21:25.700 --> 00:21:28.620 align:middle line:90%
is if the variable is up here.

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:30.870 align:middle line:90%
But now it's down here.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:36.290 align:middle line:84%
Because it's down here, the
derivative is minus this.

00:21:36.290 --> 00:21:36.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:36.790 --> 00:21:38.510 align:middle line:90%
Let me explain that.

00:21:38.510 --> 00:21:43.390 align:middle line:84%
So you get from the fundamental
theorem of calculus,

00:21:43.390 --> 00:21:47.510 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of this function,
I claim, is minus this thing

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:48.010 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:54.180 align:middle line:90%


00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:57.030 align:middle line:84%
And then this should
be evaluated at x.

00:21:57.030 --> 00:22:03.510 align:middle line:84%
This is the arccosine
at x is equal to that.

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:05.530 align:middle line:90%
So now let's just see that.

00:22:05.530 --> 00:22:07.150 align:middle line:90%
So why is this the case?

00:22:07.150 --> 00:22:16.910 align:middle line:84%
So you take-- so
remember that if you

00:22:16.910 --> 00:22:20.950 align:middle line:84%
have a function f
of x and this is

00:22:20.950 --> 00:22:27.310 align:middle line:84%
given as you're integrating from
some a to some x, a is fixed.

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:33.640 align:middle line:84%
And then you're integrating
a function like this.

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:35.510 align:middle line:84%
Assuming that the
function is nice,

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:40.200 align:middle line:84%
et cetera, then we have
that the fundamental theorem

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:42.360 align:middle line:90%
of calculus--

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:44.640 align:middle line:84%
fundamental theorem
of calculus--

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:51.600 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of this
function is little f.

00:22:51.600 --> 00:22:53.880 align:middle line:90%
But suppose I now switch.

00:22:53.880 --> 00:22:57.880 align:middle line:84%
So now suppose I now look--
so I don't look at this,

00:22:57.880 --> 00:23:00.500 align:middle line:90%
but I look at--

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:09.760 align:middle line:84%
suppose that g of x is
the integral from x to a--

00:23:09.760 --> 00:23:12.280 align:middle line:84%
let's call it x to b,
just because we usually

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:20.200 align:middle line:84%
have the endpoint as
the last point, as b.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:23.480 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that the
function is like this.

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:25.980 align:middle line:90%
What is the derivative?

00:23:25.980 --> 00:23:30.080 align:middle line:84%
But this is just the
fundamental theorem.

00:23:30.080 --> 00:23:35.540 align:middle line:84%
But one of the rules we
had writing the integral

00:23:35.540 --> 00:23:38.280 align:middle line:90%
is we can write this one here.

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:41.940 align:middle line:84%
So here I'm thinking about
that a function little f

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:44.640 align:middle line:84%
is defined on some
interval from a to b.

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:48.220 align:middle line:90%


00:23:48.220 --> 00:23:51.940 align:middle line:84%
And I can rewrite this
thing here in this form

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:55.460 align:middle line:84%
here because I can just
think about this thing

00:23:55.460 --> 00:24:04.300 align:middle line:84%
here as the integral
from a to b of f of s.

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:05.120 align:middle line:90%
So sorry.

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:06.670 align:middle line:90%
Let me write it over here.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:16.156 align:middle line:90%


00:24:16.156 --> 00:24:22.680 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just making the trivial
observation that we have--

00:24:22.680 --> 00:24:28.590 align:middle line:84%
so if we have a function
from a to b into R,

00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:33.110 align:middle line:84%
and we have some x that
lie between a and b,

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:36.270 align:middle line:84%
then we proved that
the integral from a

00:24:36.270 --> 00:24:43.550 align:middle line:84%
to b of f, this thing here, is
equal to the integral from a

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:51.250 align:middle line:84%
to x plus the
integral from x to b.

00:24:51.250 --> 00:24:55.590 align:middle line:90%


00:24:55.590 --> 00:25:00.970 align:middle line:84%
That was one of the rules,
that if you take this--

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:03.910 align:middle line:84%
if you have a dividing
point in this interval, then

00:25:03.910 --> 00:25:06.430 align:middle line:84%
you could integrate
over the first half

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:12.070 align:middle line:84%
and then add the integral
of the second half.

00:25:12.070 --> 00:25:17.510 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here just tells
you that this thing here you

00:25:17.510 --> 00:25:19.890 align:middle line:90%
can rewrite as this minus that.

00:25:19.890 --> 00:25:27.090 align:middle line:84%
So you have that the integral
from x to b f of s ds

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:32.730 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the integral
from a to b f of s ds

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:44.250 align:middle line:84%
minus the integral
from a to x f of s ds.

00:25:44.250 --> 00:25:46.730 align:middle line:90%
And so a and b are fixed.

00:25:46.730 --> 00:25:51.450 align:middle line:84%
And when you think about this
thing here as a function of x,

00:25:51.450 --> 00:25:53.010 align:middle line:90%
then it's equal to--

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:54.970 align:middle line:90%
this is just a constant.

00:25:54.970 --> 00:25:56.390 align:middle line:90%
And then minus this.

00:25:56.390 --> 00:26:00.430 align:middle line:84%
So when you take the derivative
of this, this is a constant.

00:26:00.430 --> 00:26:02.650 align:middle line:90%
So this derivative is 0.

00:26:02.650 --> 00:26:04.490 align:middle line:84%
The derivative of
this, well, that

00:26:04.490 --> 00:26:07.730 align:middle line:84%
is straight the fundamental
theorem of calculus.

00:26:07.730 --> 00:26:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And because of this
sign, you get minus f.

00:26:12.750 --> 00:26:14.650 align:middle line:84%
And so that's what
I applied over here,

00:26:14.650 --> 00:26:19.450 align:middle line:84%
that if it is of
this form here, then

00:26:19.450 --> 00:26:26.240 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of this
function is minus little f.

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:26.740 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:26:26.740 --> 00:26:30.540 align:middle line:90%


00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:31.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:34.080 align:middle line:90%
So this was-- this is so--

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:38.660 align:middle line:84%
so this is how the angle
is defined, if you will.

00:26:38.660 --> 00:26:44.820 align:middle line:84%
The angle is defined as the
arc length of the curve.

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:48.660 align:middle line:84%
And we can calculate it
using this formula here.

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:50.690 align:middle line:90%
And we're getting a nice--

00:26:50.690 --> 00:26:54.740 align:middle line:90%


00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:59.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we know what
this arccosine--

00:26:59.240 --> 00:27:01.660 align:middle line:84%
we know actually what
the derivative is just

00:27:01.660 --> 00:27:05.780 align:middle line:84%
from this arc length and the
fundamental theorem of calculus.

00:27:05.780 --> 00:27:07.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:09.140 align:middle line:84%
The next thing I
want to talk about

00:27:09.140 --> 00:27:13.420 align:middle line:84%
is I want to talk about
pointwise and uniform

00:27:13.420 --> 00:27:16.620 align:middle line:90%
convergence of functions.

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:19.920 align:middle line:84%
So you have a
sequence of functions.

00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:26.600 align:middle line:90%


00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:29.290 align:middle line:84%
You have a sequence
of functions fn.

00:27:29.290 --> 00:27:32.920 align:middle line:90%


00:27:32.920 --> 00:27:38.120 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you have
some interval I,

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:45.720 align:middle line:84%
and you have a sequence
of functions fn.

00:27:45.720 --> 00:27:51.530 align:middle line:84%
And you have another function
f also on this interval.

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:54.520 align:middle line:90%


00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:57.220 align:middle line:84%
Then we say-- so this
is the definition.

00:27:57.220 --> 00:28:01.240 align:middle line:90%


00:28:01.240 --> 00:28:04.600 align:middle line:84%
We say that the
sequence here converges

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:19.310 align:middle line:84%
to f pointwise if,
for all x fixed--

00:28:19.310 --> 00:28:22.970 align:middle line:90%


00:28:22.970 --> 00:28:24.790 align:middle line:90%
if you're looking at this--

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:28.930 align:middle line:84%
so x here, think about x as
being-- x could be anything,

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:30.610 align:middle line:90%
but it is fixed.

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:33.790 align:middle line:84%
And then you're looking
at this sequence here.

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:37.570 align:middle line:84%
So this is a sequence of real
numbers because x is fixed.

00:28:37.570 --> 00:28:42.590 align:middle line:84%
Then you want this thing
here to converge to f of x.

00:28:42.590 --> 00:28:43.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:28:43.090 --> 00:28:43.757 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:28:43.757 --> 00:28:45.830 align:middle line:84%
I had a quick question
about the last thing.

00:28:45.830 --> 00:28:51.330 align:middle line:84%
So how do you know that the
integral of a to b fs ds is 0?

00:28:51.330 --> 00:28:53.090 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: So no.

00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:58.910 align:middle line:84%
So the thing is that what
we're looking at here--

00:28:58.910 --> 00:28:59.890 align:middle line:90%
so I was asking--

00:28:59.890 --> 00:29:02.410 align:middle line:90%


00:29:02.410 --> 00:29:04.390 align:middle line:90%
so this here is--

00:29:04.390 --> 00:29:06.370 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a
function, capital F,

00:29:06.370 --> 00:29:09.650 align:middle line:84%
that is given like this, the
fundamental theorem of calculus

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:11.970 align:middle line:84%
gives you what
the derivative is.

00:29:11.970 --> 00:29:15.370 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just asking,
suppose that the function--

00:29:15.370 --> 00:29:20.940 align:middle line:84%
that the variable was not up
here but it was down here.

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:22.700 align:middle line:90%
What is the derivative?

00:29:22.700 --> 00:29:25.440 align:middle line:84%
And so in order to figure
out that derivative,

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:28.100 align:middle line:90%
I'm just using that--

00:29:28.100 --> 00:29:31.820 align:middle line:84%
so if I was integrating
over the whole interval,

00:29:31.820 --> 00:29:33.540 align:middle line:90%
a and b are fixed.

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:38.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is just some
number, whatever it is.

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.340 align:middle line:90%
But it's probably not 0.

00:29:40.340 --> 00:29:43.620 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it generally wouldn't be
0, but it's just some constant.

00:29:43.620 --> 00:29:49.180 align:middle line:84%
And so for each x you get
the same constant here.

00:29:49.180 --> 00:29:52.580 align:middle line:84%
And then it's equal
to this plus that.

00:29:52.580 --> 00:29:55.160 align:middle line:84%
But this is what
we're interested in.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:57.520 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just moving this
1 over on the other side.

00:29:57.520 --> 00:29:59.020 align:middle line:90%
So I get this thing here.

00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:01.580 align:middle line:84%
But remember, this
here is a constant.

00:30:01.580 --> 00:30:03.740 align:middle line:84%
So when you take the
derivative, it's 0.

00:30:03.740 --> 00:30:07.960 align:middle line:90%


00:30:07.960 --> 00:30:08.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:09.260 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:30:09.260 --> 00:30:09.980 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: For this problem--

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:10.460 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah?

00:30:10.460 --> 00:30:12.293 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: --if you were
to just substitute--

00:30:12.293 --> 00:30:14.660 align:middle line:84%
set b equal to a,
then wouldn't you

00:30:14.660 --> 00:30:18.160 align:middle line:84%
just get that a equal integral
from a to a goes to 0?

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:19.320 align:middle line:90%
And then you can get this--

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:21.208 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: But
that's-- but if--

00:30:21.208 --> 00:30:21.708 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:30:21.708 --> 00:30:24.520 align:middle line:90%


00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:26.140 align:middle line:90%
If b is equal to a--

00:30:26.140 --> 00:30:29.640 align:middle line:90%


00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:32.200 align:middle line:90%
if b is equal to a, yeah.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:34.120 align:middle line:90%
I mean, but it's not.

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:38.453 align:middle line:84%
I mean, so then this interval
is just a trivial interval.

00:30:38.453 --> 00:30:39.120 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:42.020 align:middle line:84%
But doesn't it allow you to
get to the same identity there?

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:42.937 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

00:30:42.937 --> 00:30:45.260 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is--
so the reason why--

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:47.220 align:middle line:90%
so why did I want to do it?

00:30:47.220 --> 00:30:47.760 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:53.540 align:middle line:84%
But it's like-- but it's kind
of using something implicitly.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:54.420 align:middle line:90%
You see what I mean?

00:30:54.420 --> 00:30:57.680 align:middle line:84%
I'm assuming that x
is between a and b

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:02.320 align:middle line:84%
because when we took this
interval, if x is not

00:31:02.320 --> 00:31:04.040 align:middle line:84%
between a, b, we
have to figure out,

00:31:04.040 --> 00:31:07.760 align:middle line:84%
what the hell do we mean by
this sort of integral anyway?

00:31:07.760 --> 00:31:13.560 align:middle line:84%
And so, yes, it
works, even if you

00:31:13.560 --> 00:31:16.000 align:middle line:84%
have the ordering
differently, but you just

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.970 align:middle line:84%
have to-- all I want
to point out here

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:21.690 align:middle line:84%
is that if it is downstairs
and not upstairs,

00:31:21.690 --> 00:31:26.270 align:middle line:84%
you have to just
remember the sign.

00:31:26.270 --> 00:31:26.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:26.770 --> 00:31:30.050 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.050 --> 00:31:30.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:33.690 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- so
I have a sequence

00:31:33.690 --> 00:31:35.970 align:middle line:90%
of functions on the interval.

00:31:35.970 --> 00:31:39.610 align:middle line:84%
I have another function
on the same interval.

00:31:39.610 --> 00:31:45.450 align:middle line:84%
And I will say that this
sequence is converging pointwise

00:31:45.450 --> 00:31:51.490 align:middle line:84%
to f if for all x fixed, when
we're looking at this sequence,

00:31:51.490 --> 00:31:54.610 align:middle line:90%
it converges to that.

00:31:54.610 --> 00:31:57.640 align:middle line:84%
And so let me look at
two examples of that.

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:00.650 align:middle line:90%


00:32:00.650 --> 00:32:04.470 align:middle line:90%
So the first one is--

00:32:04.470 --> 00:32:15.010 align:middle line:90%


00:32:15.010 --> 00:32:20.110 align:middle line:84%
so the first example
I want to look at,

00:32:20.110 --> 00:32:27.950 align:middle line:84%
this is where the functions fn
of x is equal to x to the n.

00:32:27.950 --> 00:32:32.530 align:middle line:90%
And x here is between 0 and 1.

00:32:32.530 --> 00:32:36.110 align:middle line:90%


00:32:36.110 --> 00:32:44.790 align:middle line:84%
And so this is my fn and my
function f, which is now,

00:32:44.790 --> 00:32:47.590 align:middle line:84%
of course, also a
function on this interval.

00:32:47.590 --> 00:32:56.790 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to 0 if x
is bigger or equal to 0

00:32:56.790 --> 00:32:59.230 align:middle line:90%
but strictly less than 1.

00:32:59.230 --> 00:33:05.350 align:middle line:90%
And it's 1 if x is equal to 1.

00:33:05.350 --> 00:33:07.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:07.030 --> 00:33:10.690 align:middle line:84%
So of course, this function
f is not continuous.

00:33:10.690 --> 00:33:12.250 align:middle line:90%
The other ones are continuous.

00:33:12.250 --> 00:33:15.960 align:middle line:90%


00:33:15.960 --> 00:33:24.920 align:middle line:84%
Now, I claim that this
sequence-- so the sequence fn

00:33:24.920 --> 00:33:28.800 align:middle line:90%
is converging pointwise to f.

00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:34.860 align:middle line:90%
So fn converges to f pointwise.

00:33:34.860 --> 00:33:39.080 align:middle line:90%


00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:44.360 align:middle line:90%
Because if you fix x--

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:56.680 align:middle line:84%
let's say, fix x, and let's
assume that it's between--

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:00.380 align:middle line:90%
sorry, it's between 0--

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:02.120 align:middle line:90%
it's strictly less than 1.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:05.000 align:middle line:90%
So you're fixing x.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.800 align:middle line:84%
And let's first deal with
the case where that x

00:34:07.800 --> 00:34:10.080 align:middle line:90%
is strictly less than 1.

00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:12.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I'm looking
at x to the n--

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:14.810 align:middle line:90%
so it takes some small number.

00:34:14.810 --> 00:34:17.449 align:middle line:84%
Small just means that
it's strictly less than 1.

00:34:17.449 --> 00:34:20.530 align:middle line:84%
And I multiply it
by itself n time.

00:34:20.530 --> 00:34:22.593 align:middle line:90%
Well, that certainly goes to 0.

00:34:22.593 --> 00:34:26.610 align:middle line:90%


00:34:26.610 --> 00:34:33.650 align:middle line:84%
If x here is fixed but it's
not 1, then x to the n.

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:36.850 align:middle line:84%
If x is 1, then this
here is still 1.

00:34:36.850 --> 00:34:40.969 align:middle line:90%


00:34:40.969 --> 00:34:42.909 align:middle line:90%
So you see that in this case--

00:34:42.909 --> 00:34:46.870 align:middle line:90%
so this here is f to the n of x.

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:50.170 align:middle line:90%
And this here is f of x.

00:34:50.170 --> 00:34:53.389 align:middle line:84%
So these things here, I mean,
they're actually equal to this.

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:55.469 align:middle line:90%
So in particular, they converge.

00:34:55.469 --> 00:34:59.810 align:middle line:90%
And this here is what f of x is.

00:34:59.810 --> 00:35:05.090 align:middle line:84%
And this here is,
again, fn of x.

00:35:05.090 --> 00:35:09.050 align:middle line:84%
So you have that this
sequence of functions

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:13.710 align:middle line:84%
converge to this
slightly crazy function.

00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:15.530 align:middle line:90%
So that's the first example.

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:16.850 align:middle line:90%
They converge pointwise.

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:19.870 align:middle line:90%


00:35:19.870 --> 00:35:24.800 align:middle line:84%
The next example I
want to look at is--

00:35:24.800 --> 00:35:28.470 align:middle line:90%


00:35:28.470 --> 00:35:35.950 align:middle line:84%
so the next example is
where the functions are--

00:35:35.950 --> 00:35:38.645 align:middle line:90%
you're just summing here.

00:35:38.645 --> 00:35:39.270 align:middle line:90%
You're summing.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:46.510 align:middle line:84%
You just take the power series
for the exponential function.

00:35:46.510 --> 00:35:51.610 align:middle line:84%
So you're summing where
k is equal to 1 to n.

00:35:51.610 --> 00:35:54.610 align:middle line:90%
And that's my fn of x.

00:35:54.610 --> 00:35:57.190 align:middle line:90%


00:35:57.190 --> 00:36:03.510 align:middle line:84%
And then my f of x is
the infinite sum, which

00:36:03.510 --> 00:36:06.590 align:middle line:90%
is the exponential function.

00:36:06.590 --> 00:36:10.920 align:middle line:84%
And we have already
proved that if you fix x--

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:12.340 align:middle line:90%
so we fix x--

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:20.560 align:middle line:84%
then this fn here of x converges
to f of x for each fixed x.

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:23.310 align:middle line:90%
For each fixed x.

00:36:23.310 --> 00:36:30.960 align:middle line:90%


00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:34.880 align:middle line:84%
So this sequence of
functions pointwise converges

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:38.760 align:middle line:90%
to the exponential function.

00:36:38.760 --> 00:36:42.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is one notion of
convergence for functions.

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:46.660 align:middle line:84%
And there's another notion
that is also useful.

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:48.360 align:middle line:90%
They're both useful.

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:50.040 align:middle line:90%
The other one is stronger.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:53.240 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, if you
have the stronger version,

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:57.720 align:middle line:84%
you often get
something much better.

00:36:57.720 --> 00:36:59.100 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I shouldn't
have erased this.

00:36:59.100 --> 00:37:00.720 align:middle line:90%
But anyway.

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:05.480 align:middle line:90%
And so the second notion is--

00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:13.840 align:middle line:84%
so this is the notion
of uniform convergence.

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:21.540 align:middle line:90%


00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:27.600 align:middle line:84%
Uniform means that
it's uniform in x.

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:33.500 align:middle line:84%
So what we have here is we
have a sequence of functions

00:37:33.500 --> 00:37:37.780 align:middle line:84%
and f defined on
some interval into R.

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:40.700 align:middle line:84%
And then we say that
this sequence converges

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:56.460 align:middle line:84%
to f uniformly if, for all
epsilon greater than 0,

00:37:56.460 --> 00:38:00.900 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N so
that if little n is bigger

00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:08.910 align:middle line:84%
than this capital N,
then f of x minus fn of x

00:38:08.910 --> 00:38:13.050 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than
epsilon for all x.

00:38:13.050 --> 00:38:16.670 align:middle line:90%


00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:24.150 align:middle line:84%
And again, the uniformness,
it holds for all x.

00:38:24.150 --> 00:38:28.170 align:middle line:84%
You can use the same
capital N for all x.

00:38:28.170 --> 00:38:33.030 align:middle line:90%


00:38:33.030 --> 00:38:45.550 align:middle line:84%
And so now, now what you have
is that if a sequence converges

00:38:45.550 --> 00:38:50.590 align:middle line:84%
uniformly, then it
converges pointwise.

00:38:50.590 --> 00:38:54.950 align:middle line:84%
So we have the following
lemma that follows directly

00:38:54.950 --> 00:38:58.110 align:middle line:90%
from the definition.

00:38:58.110 --> 00:38:58.660 align:middle line:90%
So lemma.

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:01.510 align:middle line:90%


00:39:01.510 --> 00:39:16.890 align:middle line:84%
So a uniform
convergence of fn to f

00:39:16.890 --> 00:39:37.730 align:middle line:84%
implies pointwise
convergence of fn to f.

00:39:37.730 --> 00:39:38.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:38.350 --> 00:39:43.330 align:middle line:84%
So uniform convergence
implies pointwise convergence.

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:44.910 align:middle line:90%
And that's clear.

00:39:44.910 --> 00:39:47.610 align:middle line:84%
That's really just
the definition

00:39:47.610 --> 00:39:51.090 align:middle line:84%
if I had written out
what it means for--

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:54.050 align:middle line:84%
so this here, I've
written out what it means

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:57.330 align:middle line:90%
to have uniform convergence.

00:39:57.330 --> 00:39:59.530 align:middle line:84%
If it was pointwise
convergence, then

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:01.190 align:middle line:90%
you have these functions again.

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:04.420 align:middle line:84%
And you have that this
converges to that pointwise.

00:40:04.420 --> 00:40:07.360 align:middle line:90%
It means that the sequence fn--

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:12.340 align:middle line:84%
so once you fix x, then
the sequence fn of x--

00:40:12.340 --> 00:40:23.820 align:middle line:84%
so once x is fixed, then
these here converge to this.

00:40:23.820 --> 00:40:26.660 align:middle line:84%
But saying that this
sequence here converge

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:29.380 align:middle line:84%
means that for all
epsilon greater than 0,

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:35.820 align:middle line:84%
there exists an N. But this N
is now allowed to depend on x so

00:40:35.820 --> 00:40:39.340 align:middle line:84%
that if little n is bigger
than this capital N,

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:46.380 align:middle line:84%
then fn of x minus f of x
is smaller than epsilon.

00:40:46.380 --> 00:40:52.220 align:middle line:84%
So you see that clearly uniform
convergence implies pointwise.

00:40:52.220 --> 00:40:55.820 align:middle line:84%
And again, uniform just
means that this capital N

00:40:55.820 --> 00:40:58.320 align:middle line:84%
can be chosen to be
the same for all x.

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:01.780 align:middle line:90%


00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:04.850 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look
at the examples.

00:41:04.850 --> 00:41:09.070 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, I erased
the most important one.

00:41:09.070 --> 00:41:11.530 align:middle line:84%
So I will just go
through it again.

00:41:11.530 --> 00:41:15.670 align:middle line:84%
Let me just talk about
the example again.

00:41:15.670 --> 00:41:22.450 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll see why
this example here does not.

00:41:22.450 --> 00:41:25.550 align:middle line:84%
So we have this
example from before,

00:41:25.550 --> 00:41:32.550 align:middle line:84%
where the sequence of
functions was x to the n.

00:41:32.550 --> 00:41:36.270 align:middle line:90%
And x here was between 0 and 1.

00:41:36.270 --> 00:41:39.870 align:middle line:84%
And then we had
this function f that

00:41:39.870 --> 00:41:43.270 align:middle line:84%
was this function that
was not continuous.

00:41:43.270 --> 00:41:47.150 align:middle line:84%
But this function was
given to be equal to 0

00:41:47.150 --> 00:41:53.950 align:middle line:84%
if x here is
strictly less than 1

00:41:53.950 --> 00:41:59.602 align:middle line:90%
and it was 1 if x is equal to 1.

00:41:59.602 --> 00:42:03.116 align:middle line:90%
That was this function f.

00:42:03.116 --> 00:42:07.410 align:middle line:84%
And we know-- we've already
shown that the fn converges

00:42:07.410 --> 00:42:09.010 align:middle line:90%
to f pointwise.

00:42:09.010 --> 00:42:12.150 align:middle line:90%
But we want to see now--

00:42:12.150 --> 00:42:21.330 align:middle line:84%
so I claim that fn
does not converge.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:29.690 align:middle line:84%
So this does not
converge uniformly to f.

00:42:29.690 --> 00:42:33.150 align:middle line:84%
We know already that
it converges pointwise.

00:42:33.150 --> 00:42:39.050 align:middle line:84%
And I claim that this sequence
does not converge uniformly.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:42.850 align:middle line:90%
So now, why is this the case?

00:42:42.850 --> 00:42:47.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is because, you
see, by the intermediate value

00:42:47.850 --> 00:42:54.330 align:middle line:84%
theorem, the functions
fn are continuous.

00:42:54.330 --> 00:42:57.490 align:middle line:90%
At 0, they take the value 0.

00:42:57.490 --> 00:43:00.300 align:middle line:90%
At 1, they take the value 1.

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:04.360 align:middle line:84%
So for each n, by the
intermediate value theorem--

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:22.220 align:middle line:90%


00:43:22.220 --> 00:43:40.220 align:middle line:84%
since each fn is continuous,
then there exists an xn,

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:44.140 align:middle line:90%
but it really will depend on n.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:52.800 align:middle line:84%
So that fn of xn will
take the value one half.

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:55.200 align:middle line:90%
So the functions here--

00:43:55.200 --> 00:43:56.820 align:middle line:90%
this is the functions--

00:43:56.820 --> 00:43:57.500 align:middle line:90%
oops.

00:43:57.500 --> 00:44:00.320 align:middle line:90%
This is the functions.

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:04.760 align:middle line:90%
This is the function fn.

00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:07.240 align:middle line:90%
At 0, it takes a value of 0.

00:44:07.240 --> 00:44:10.620 align:middle line:90%
At 1, it takes a value 1.

00:44:10.620 --> 00:44:16.100 align:middle line:84%
So there is somewhere
where a half is achieved.

00:44:16.100 --> 00:44:18.060 align:middle line:90%
And this is at this-- it's here.

00:44:18.060 --> 00:44:21.700 align:middle line:90%


00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:23.100 align:middle line:90%
So you have that.

00:44:23.100 --> 00:44:27.560 align:middle line:84%
And again, this xn
is depending on n.

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:30.800 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is
that as n gets large,

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:36.040 align:middle line:84%
this point will have to
move very close to 1.

00:44:36.040 --> 00:44:44.640 align:middle line:84%
But if you're now looking
at fn of x minus f of x--

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:51.440 align:middle line:90%


00:44:51.440 --> 00:44:52.800 align:middle line:90%
so we want to--

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:55.240 align:middle line:84%
if it was converging
uniformly, it

00:44:55.240 --> 00:44:58.770 align:middle line:84%
would mean that this difference
here would be smaller

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:01.810 align:middle line:90%
than some epsilon for all x.

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:09.170 align:middle line:84%
But if you're just looking
at this point here,

00:45:09.170 --> 00:45:12.210 align:middle line:84%
this difference
here is this point

00:45:12.210 --> 00:45:16.610 align:middle line:90%
here, xn, will lie strictly--

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:22.210 align:middle line:84%
xn here will lie-- this is
where this value here is a half.

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:23.590 align:middle line:90%
It's not 1.

00:45:23.590 --> 00:45:28.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's strictly
between 0 and 1.

00:45:28.770 --> 00:45:37.210 align:middle line:84%
So you see that for each
n, this function f at xn,

00:45:37.210 --> 00:45:38.950 align:middle line:90%
this will always be 0.

00:45:38.950 --> 00:45:43.110 align:middle line:84%
This is because the
function f is 0 except at 1.

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:45.850 align:middle line:84%
And this point is
definitely not 1.

00:45:45.850 --> 00:45:47.450 align:middle line:90%
So you have that.

00:45:47.450 --> 00:45:53.130 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this thing
here, this here is 0.

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:56.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is just the value
of this, the absolute value.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:57.720 align:middle line:90%
But that's actually a half.

00:45:57.720 --> 00:46:01.580 align:middle line:90%
So this is always a half.

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:06.020 align:middle line:84%
So the function would converge
uniformly as long as--

00:46:06.020 --> 00:46:09.260 align:middle line:90%


00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:13.700 align:middle line:84%
so uniform convergence
would mean--

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:15.560 align:middle line:90%
so uniform convergence.

00:46:15.560 --> 00:46:21.140 align:middle line:90%


00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:29.540 align:middle line:90%
So now let's show.

00:46:29.540 --> 00:46:40.240 align:middle line:84%
So let's prove that fn does
not converge uniformly to f.

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:45.300 align:middle line:90%


00:46:45.300 --> 00:46:51.500 align:middle line:90%
And so I just pick my epsilon.

00:46:51.500 --> 00:46:57.810 align:middle line:84%
So I pick an epsilon
less than half.

00:46:57.810 --> 00:47:03.270 align:middle line:84%
And then if it was
converging-- and suppose not--

00:47:03.270 --> 00:47:08.000 align:middle line:90%


00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:17.700 align:middle line:84%
that is, suppose fn
converges to f uniformly.

00:47:17.700 --> 00:47:21.440 align:middle line:90%


00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:23.180 align:middle line:90%
This means that for all epsilon.

00:47:23.180 --> 00:47:25.140 align:middle line:84%
But I just use
this epsilon here.

00:47:25.140 --> 00:47:29.040 align:middle line:90%
I just use this one, epsilon.

00:47:29.040 --> 00:47:37.440 align:middle line:84%
But then I would have that
there exists capital N so that--

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:42.040 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I can even take
it to be equal to a half.

00:47:42.040 --> 00:47:47.560 align:middle line:84%
So there exists
capital N such that

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:53.930 align:middle line:84%
if little n is bigger than
capital N, then this thing here,

00:47:53.930 --> 00:48:01.850 align:middle line:84%
minus f of x, would have to
be strictly less than half

00:48:01.850 --> 00:48:02.910 align:middle line:90%
for all x.

00:48:02.910 --> 00:48:06.730 align:middle line:90%


00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:09.970 align:middle line:84%
If it was converging
uniformly, then in particular,

00:48:09.970 --> 00:48:15.970 align:middle line:84%
for this one choice of epsilon,
you would have this for all x.

00:48:15.970 --> 00:48:19.310 align:middle line:84%
But we already know that
if we are looking at--

00:48:19.310 --> 00:48:22.530 align:middle line:84%
now depending on what
this is, but that's fine.

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:26.450 align:middle line:84%
If you insert x equal
to xn, then this

00:48:26.450 --> 00:48:28.990 align:middle line:90%
is actually equal to a half.

00:48:28.990 --> 00:48:31.410 align:middle line:90%
So this here does not hold.

00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:32.830 align:middle line:90%
This is the contradiction.

00:48:32.830 --> 00:48:39.090 align:middle line:90%


00:48:39.090 --> 00:48:42.680 align:middle line:84%
Now, in the other example
that we looked at before--

00:48:42.680 --> 00:48:50.810 align:middle line:90%


00:48:50.810 --> 00:48:54.840 align:middle line:84%
in the other example
we have that--

00:48:54.840 --> 00:48:58.830 align:middle line:90%


00:48:58.830 --> 00:49:03.470 align:middle line:84%
in the other example,
which is this example here,

00:49:03.470 --> 00:49:06.410 align:middle line:84%
this sequence here
is converging.

00:49:06.410 --> 00:49:10.590 align:middle line:84%
And I'll return to
this in a minute.

00:49:10.590 --> 00:49:14.470 align:middle line:84%
So in this case,
these here converge

00:49:14.470 --> 00:49:26.350 align:middle line:84%
to f uniformly on
each interval--

00:49:26.350 --> 00:49:27.850 align:middle line:90%
on each bounded interval.

00:49:27.850 --> 00:49:35.550 align:middle line:84%
So each interval
of the form minus L

00:49:35.550 --> 00:49:38.870 align:middle line:84%
to L. So on each
bounded interval.

00:49:38.870 --> 00:49:39.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:39.670 --> 00:49:42.540 align:middle line:84%
And we will talk about
this more in just a second.

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:45.910 align:middle line:90%


00:49:45.910 --> 00:49:48.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:58.200 align:middle line:84%
And because this is
the content of what's

00:49:58.200 --> 00:50:01.480 align:middle line:90%
called Weierstrass M-test.

00:50:01.480 --> 00:50:06.800 align:middle line:84%
So this holds more generally
that if you take a sequence--

00:50:06.800 --> 00:50:07.560 align:middle line:90%
so let's see.

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:09.420 align:middle line:90%
Weierstrass M-test.

00:50:09.420 --> 00:50:14.840 align:middle line:90%


00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:31.600 align:middle line:84%
So in Weierstrass M-test,
you have a sequence

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:36.980 align:middle line:84%
of functions, fn, and you
have that these sequence--

00:50:36.980 --> 00:50:45.640 align:middle line:84%
so fn, sorry, is functions
on some interval into R.

00:50:45.640 --> 00:50:58.770 align:middle line:84%
And then you have that the fn
are bounded by some constant Mn.

00:50:58.770 --> 00:51:02.810 align:middle line:90%
And then you have that the Mn--

00:51:02.810 --> 00:51:05.070 align:middle line:84%
so these are clearly
non-negative numbers.

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:08.630 align:middle line:84%
And you have that
this series here--

00:51:08.630 --> 00:51:12.010 align:middle line:90%


00:51:12.010 --> 00:51:16.190 align:middle line:90%
this here is finite.

00:51:16.190 --> 00:51:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So this is a series of
non-negative numbers.

00:51:19.470 --> 00:51:23.290 align:middle line:84%
So to say that this
series is summable

00:51:23.290 --> 00:51:24.940 align:middle line:84%
is the same as saying
that it's finite.

00:51:24.940 --> 00:51:29.330 align:middle line:90%


00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:33.130 align:middle line:84%
And now the claim is-- so
then Weierstrass M-test is--

00:51:33.130 --> 00:51:38.130 align:middle line:90%


00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:41.910 align:middle line:84%
so this is that if
this here is the case,

00:51:41.910 --> 00:51:49.570 align:middle line:84%
then this sequence converges
to some f uniformly.

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:53.870 align:middle line:90%


00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:56.480 align:middle line:90%
That's Weierstrass M-test.

00:51:56.480 --> 00:51:59.790 align:middle line:90%


00:51:59.790 --> 00:52:00.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:52:00.990 --> 00:52:02.510 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What does
this mean here?

00:52:02.510 --> 00:52:05.168 align:middle line:84%
Is it the absolute
value of the function?

00:52:05.168 --> 00:52:06.210 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Oh, yeah.

00:52:06.210 --> 00:52:09.870 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- so
this here means--

00:52:09.870 --> 00:52:15.350 align:middle line:84%
this here just means
that fn of x is less than

00:52:15.350 --> 00:52:17.730 align:middle line:90%
or equal to M for all x.

00:52:17.730 --> 00:52:25.070 align:middle line:90%


00:52:25.070 --> 00:52:26.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:31.370 align:middle line:84%
That's a kind of quite
common used situation.

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:34.030 align:middle line:90%


00:52:34.030 --> 00:52:35.918 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:35.918 --> 00:52:37.620 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove that.

00:52:37.620 --> 00:52:45.270 align:middle line:90%


00:52:45.270 --> 00:52:47.410 align:middle line:90%
So we are looking at--

00:52:47.410 --> 00:52:53.000 align:middle line:90%


00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:54.900 align:middle line:90%
so suppose we look at--

00:52:54.900 --> 00:52:58.080 align:middle line:90%
suppose we define Sn of x.

00:52:58.080 --> 00:53:03.880 align:middle line:84%
So this is just when you're
summing from k equal to 0

00:53:03.880 --> 00:53:08.160 align:middle line:90%
to n of fk of x.

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:10.240 align:middle line:90%
Suppose you're looking at this.

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:12.160 align:middle line:90%
And you want to prove--

00:53:12.160 --> 00:53:13.410 align:middle line:90%
so I want to show--

00:53:13.410 --> 00:53:20.320 align:middle line:90%


00:53:20.320 --> 00:53:21.940 align:middle line:90%
yeah, sorry about that.

00:53:21.940 --> 00:53:23.460 align:middle line:84%
This is not what
we want to prove.

00:53:23.460 --> 00:53:25.360 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:53:25.360 --> 00:53:27.880 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I should have said.

00:53:27.880 --> 00:53:28.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:53:28.720 --> 00:53:31.220 align:middle line:84%
It's not these
functions that converge.

00:53:31.220 --> 00:53:33.560 align:middle line:90%
It's the sum of them.

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:36.000 align:middle line:84%
So what I want to
prove is that--

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.560 align:middle line:84%
I want to prove that
this thing here--

00:53:38.560 --> 00:53:45.780 align:middle line:84%
as k equal to 0 to n,
that this function here

00:53:45.780 --> 00:53:50.270 align:middle line:90%
converge uniformly.

00:53:50.270 --> 00:53:50.770 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:53:50.770 --> 00:53:53.740 align:middle line:90%


00:53:53.740 --> 00:53:56.140 align:middle line:90%
So think about it.

00:53:56.140 --> 00:54:02.740 align:middle line:84%
You want this to probably
apply to some power series.

00:54:02.740 --> 00:54:09.700 align:middle line:84%
And so the individual fk
is like this polynomial.

00:54:09.700 --> 00:54:13.860 align:middle line:90%
It's of some degree.

00:54:13.860 --> 00:54:16.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:20.020 align:middle line:90%
So we define this function Sn.

00:54:20.020 --> 00:54:26.170 align:middle line:84%
And I want to prove this
Sn and then converge.

00:54:26.170 --> 00:54:30.220 align:middle line:90%


00:54:30.220 --> 00:54:33.660 align:middle line:84%
And if it's OK, I
think it's better

00:54:33.660 --> 00:54:37.620 align:middle line:84%
to call this something else
than little f, to call it S,

00:54:37.620 --> 00:54:40.800 align:middle line:84%
because it's not these
guys that converge.

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:42.270 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum of
them that converge.

00:54:42.270 --> 00:54:46.288 align:middle line:90%


00:54:46.288 --> 00:54:52.910 align:middle line:84%
So we want to show that these
guys here, the Sn converts

00:54:52.910 --> 00:54:54.640 align:middle line:90%
to this S uniform.

00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:59.310 align:middle line:90%


00:54:59.310 --> 00:55:02.590 align:middle line:90%
That's what we want to prove.

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:06.830 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's look
at the difference

00:55:06.830 --> 00:55:14.150 align:middle line:90%
between Sn of x and Sm of x.

00:55:14.150 --> 00:55:21.710 align:middle line:84%
And so here I'm going to think
about n as being larger than m.

00:55:21.710 --> 00:55:24.010 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I'm thinking
about this thing here.

00:55:24.010 --> 00:55:26.550 align:middle line:90%


00:55:26.550 --> 00:55:32.910 align:middle line:84%
Well, this here is when
you're summing the first--

00:55:32.910 --> 00:55:35.870 align:middle line:84%
I guess you're starting
at k equal to 0.

00:55:35.870 --> 00:55:42.330 align:middle line:84%
So then we're summing the
first n plus 1 of those guys.

00:55:42.330 --> 00:55:43.783 align:middle line:90%
Here, we're summing more.

00:55:43.783 --> 00:55:45.450 align:middle line:84%
We're summing those
guys, but then we're

00:55:45.450 --> 00:55:47.610 align:middle line:90%
also summing some more.

00:55:47.610 --> 00:55:50.730 align:middle line:90%
And so this thing here--

00:55:50.730 --> 00:55:52.710 align:middle line:90%
so let me just write it out.

00:55:52.710 --> 00:55:59.450 align:middle line:90%
So k equal to 0 to n of fk of x.

00:55:59.450 --> 00:56:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And the second one is
when we're summing.

00:56:03.250 --> 00:56:04.550 align:middle line:90%
n is bigger than m.

00:56:04.550 --> 00:56:06.360 align:middle line:84%
So here, we are
actually summing fewer.

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:10.050 align:middle line:90%


00:56:10.050 --> 00:56:14.890 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, the difference
is between these two are,

00:56:14.890 --> 00:56:21.010 align:middle line:84%
how many more of these guys
are there than those guys?

00:56:21.010 --> 00:56:23.610 align:middle line:84%
So this is summing
absolute value,

00:56:23.610 --> 00:56:33.410 align:middle line:84%
where we're summing from k equal
to m plus 1 up to n of fk of x.

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:35.870 align:middle line:90%
So that's what it's equal to.

00:56:35.870 --> 00:56:37.950 align:middle line:84%
And we didn't even have
to have absolute value.

00:56:37.950 --> 00:56:41.460 align:middle line:84%
But in a minute, it's useful
to have absolute value.

00:56:41.460 --> 00:56:44.060 align:middle line:84%
Because now, of
course, this sum here

00:56:44.060 --> 00:56:49.730 align:middle line:84%
is less than the sum of
the absolute values k

00:56:49.730 --> 00:56:53.500 align:middle line:90%
equal to m plus 1 to n.

00:56:53.500 --> 00:56:56.420 align:middle line:84%
And then we take
the absolute value

00:56:56.420 --> 00:57:00.510 align:middle line:84%
in under the summation
sign, like this.

00:57:00.510 --> 00:57:04.740 align:middle line:84%
But now we can use
our condition here.

00:57:04.740 --> 00:57:11.700 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is less than
or equal to the sum here from k

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:16.580 align:middle line:90%
equal to m plus 1 up to n of Mk.

00:57:16.580 --> 00:57:22.260 align:middle line:90%


00:57:22.260 --> 00:57:29.880 align:middle line:84%
But those guys, this is just
a sequence of real numbers.

00:57:29.880 --> 00:57:30.880 align:middle line:90%
This is not a function.

00:57:30.880 --> 00:57:32.380 align:middle line:90%
It's just real numbers.

00:57:32.380 --> 00:57:33.900 align:middle line:90%
And they converge.

00:57:33.900 --> 00:57:36.020 align:middle line:90%
So this means that--

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:39.430 align:middle line:90%
so this means that given--

00:57:39.430 --> 00:57:45.670 align:middle line:84%
this means that you have-- that
you can make this thing here

00:57:45.670 --> 00:57:50.790 align:middle line:84%
as small as you want, as long
as m is sufficiently large.

00:57:50.790 --> 00:57:54.190 align:middle line:90%


00:57:54.190 --> 00:58:06.400 align:middle line:90%
So given-- so given--

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:09.630 align:middle line:90%


00:58:09.630 --> 00:58:13.830 align:middle line:84%
so given epsilon
greater than 0, there

00:58:13.830 --> 00:58:19.510 align:middle line:84%
exists a capital N
such that if m here

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:28.870 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than capital N,
then the sum here of the tail,

00:58:28.870 --> 00:58:37.230 align:middle line:84%
this thing here, up to
anything else of this Mk,

00:58:37.230 --> 00:58:38.890 align:middle line:90%
that this is less than epsilon.

00:58:38.890 --> 00:58:41.410 align:middle line:90%


00:58:41.410 --> 00:58:44.470 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
this is really saying--

00:58:44.470 --> 00:58:50.450 align:middle line:84%
so this implies that
the Sn for each x--

00:58:50.450 --> 00:58:55.410 align:middle line:84%
for each x, you can think about
this thing here as a sequence.

00:58:55.410 --> 00:58:59.490 align:middle line:84%
And so you have that
now this sequence

00:58:59.490 --> 00:59:02.670 align:middle line:90%
here is a Cauchy sequence.

00:59:02.670 --> 00:59:05.300 align:middle line:84%
For each x, this here
is a Cauchy sequence.

00:59:05.300 --> 00:59:13.370 align:middle line:90%


00:59:13.370 --> 00:59:17.410 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this Sn of x, they

00:59:17.410 --> 00:59:19.770 align:middle line:84%
will actually
converge to something.

00:59:19.770 --> 00:59:23.170 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
I call S of x.

00:59:23.170 --> 00:59:26.410 align:middle line:84%
So that gives you
a function S of x.

00:59:26.410 --> 00:59:30.350 align:middle line:84%
But it gives you
more because you see,

00:59:30.350 --> 00:59:33.050 align:middle line:84%
it actually shows
you something about--

00:59:33.050 --> 00:59:39.380 align:middle line:84%
because this inequality here,
that this difference here

00:59:39.380 --> 00:59:40.740 align:middle line:90%
is less than that.

00:59:40.740 --> 00:59:44.820 align:middle line:90%
That holds for all x.

00:59:44.820 --> 00:59:48.300 align:middle line:90%
So this means that--

00:59:48.300 --> 00:59:51.860 align:middle line:84%
this means that as
you're sending--

00:59:51.860 --> 00:59:55.630 align:middle line:90%
so this means that you have--

00:59:55.630 --> 00:59:58.740 align:middle line:90%


00:59:58.740 --> 01:00:01.700 align:middle line:90%
so now let n go to infinity.

01:00:01.700 --> 01:00:04.320 align:middle line:84%
If you take this
inequality here--

01:00:04.320 --> 01:00:07.420 align:middle line:84%
so you we have
this inequality, Sn

01:00:07.420 --> 01:00:15.820 align:middle line:84%
of x minus Sm of x is less
than or equal to the sum

01:00:15.820 --> 01:00:22.860 align:middle line:84%
here, k equal to n
plus 1 to n of Mk.

01:00:22.860 --> 01:00:24.680 align:middle line:90%
So we have this inequality.

01:00:24.680 --> 01:00:28.900 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, you can
write it as if you're

01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:30.340 align:middle line:90%
summing over the entirety.

01:00:30.340 --> 01:00:37.600 align:middle line:90%


01:00:37.600 --> 01:00:40.920 align:middle line:84%
And so now this side
of it, this side

01:00:40.920 --> 01:00:43.920 align:middle line:90%
does not depend on little n.

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:46.640 align:middle line:84%
This here holds as
long as all here we

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:50.680 align:middle line:84%
require was that this
here was bigger than that.

01:00:50.680 --> 01:00:54.080 align:middle line:84%
And so as n goes
to infinity, you

01:00:54.080 --> 01:01:02.780 align:middle line:84%
have that S of x minus Sm of
x will have to be less than

01:01:02.780 --> 01:01:03.950 align:middle line:90%
or equal to the sum.

01:01:03.950 --> 01:01:06.960 align:middle line:90%


01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:11.800 align:middle line:84%
And the key point here for
this Weierstrass M-test

01:01:11.800 --> 01:01:15.280 align:middle line:90%
is that this here holds for all.

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:19.160 align:middle line:90%
This inequality holds for all x.

01:01:19.160 --> 01:01:20.980 align:middle line:90%
You see that little n is gone.

01:01:20.980 --> 01:01:26.080 align:middle line:84%
There's only this
capital N. Sorry, the M.

01:01:26.080 --> 01:01:29.780 align:middle line:90%
And so now we again--

01:01:29.780 --> 01:01:35.630 align:middle line:84%
so as long as you choose
some N insufficiently large,

01:01:35.630 --> 01:01:39.530 align:middle line:84%
then if little m is
bigger or equal to this N,

01:01:39.530 --> 01:01:43.930 align:middle line:84%
then you can make this sum here
that have no reference to x.

01:01:43.930 --> 01:01:45.916 align:middle line:84%
You can make this
less than epsilon.

01:01:45.916 --> 01:01:48.730 align:middle line:90%


01:01:48.730 --> 01:01:51.370 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
less than epsilon.

01:01:51.370 --> 01:01:53.930 align:middle line:84%
And you have this
inequality for all x.

01:01:53.930 --> 01:01:57.710 align:middle line:84%
So you have this one here
less than this for all x.

01:01:57.710 --> 01:01:59.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly
uniform convergence.

01:01:59.830 --> 01:02:00.530 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:02:00.530 --> 01:02:03.090 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Where did
we get the first--

01:02:03.090 --> 01:02:05.890 align:middle line:84%
when we said that the
sum of these Mk's are

01:02:05.890 --> 01:02:08.590 align:middle line:84%
less than epsilon, where
did that come from?

01:02:08.590 --> 01:02:13.050 align:middle line:90%


01:02:13.050 --> 01:02:16.970 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: So let me just--

01:02:16.970 --> 01:02:19.750 align:middle line:84%
I'll get to this
in just a second.

01:02:19.750 --> 01:02:23.690 align:middle line:84%
But let me just say what
is the strategy here.

01:02:23.690 --> 01:02:27.016 align:middle line:90%
So we have this sequence.

01:02:27.016 --> 01:02:30.170 align:middle line:90%


01:02:30.170 --> 01:02:32.220 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I erased the
statement, unfortunately.

01:02:32.220 --> 01:02:38.660 align:middle line:84%
So we have this sequence of
functions on an interval.

01:02:38.660 --> 01:02:45.380 align:middle line:84%
And you had that this function
here was bounded like this.

01:02:45.380 --> 01:02:49.900 align:middle line:84%
And then you had that these
are just real numbers.

01:02:49.900 --> 01:02:56.900 align:middle line:84%
And you had that these real
numbers here were summable.

01:02:56.900 --> 01:03:01.164 align:middle line:84%
So these are non-negative,
real numbers, of course.

01:03:01.164 --> 01:03:05.020 align:middle line:90%
And so then-- and I claim--

01:03:05.020 --> 01:03:10.820 align:middle line:84%
so the claim is that the sum
here of these guys, these

01:03:10.820 --> 01:03:17.620 align:middle line:84%
here, I claim that these guys
here converge uniformly to some

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:20.340 align:middle line:90%
function S of x.

01:03:20.340 --> 01:03:25.460 align:middle line:84%
The first step is to
say that they actually--

01:03:25.460 --> 01:03:28.700 align:middle line:84%
that there exists
some function S,

01:03:28.700 --> 01:03:32.480 align:middle line:84%
and they converge to
that function pointwise.

01:03:32.480 --> 01:03:40.240 align:middle line:84%
In order to prove that, I
proved that these sums here,

01:03:40.240 --> 01:03:43.700 align:middle line:84%
for each fixed x, is
a Cauchy sequence.

01:03:43.700 --> 01:03:47.320 align:middle line:84%
Once there is a Cauchy
sequence for each fixed x,

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:49.800 align:middle line:90%
then they will be convergent.

01:03:49.800 --> 01:03:55.000 align:middle line:84%
And the limits are now
defined to be S of x.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:57.200 align:middle line:90%
So that gives me a function.

01:03:57.200 --> 01:03:58.840 align:middle line:84%
And then the thing
is that I have

01:03:58.840 --> 01:04:01.240 align:middle line:84%
to upgrade this
convergence, which

01:04:01.240 --> 01:04:06.220 align:middle line:84%
initially is pointwise
to uniform convergence.

01:04:06.220 --> 01:04:08.580 align:middle line:90%
And so now you are asking--

01:04:08.580 --> 01:04:10.200 align:middle line:90%
so now--

01:04:10.200 --> 01:04:14.440 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why did-- so we got
the sum of Mk's But then where

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:14.960 align:middle line:90%
did we--

01:04:14.960 --> 01:04:16.292 align:middle line:90%
how did we just [INAUDIBLE]?

01:04:16.292 --> 01:04:17.500 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: That's right.

01:04:17.500 --> 01:04:21.600 align:middle line:84%
And so now-- so this here
was just very general.

01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:25.180 align:middle line:84%
And it just used
this inequality.

01:04:25.180 --> 01:04:27.360 align:middle line:90%
That's all it used.

01:04:27.360 --> 01:04:31.370 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm using that
these guys are summable.

01:04:31.370 --> 01:04:34.410 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if I'm
starting this summation

01:04:34.410 --> 01:04:37.370 align:middle line:84%
sufficiently far
out, then I can make

01:04:37.370 --> 01:04:39.676 align:middle line:90%
it less than a given epsilon.

01:04:39.676 --> 01:04:40.490 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

01:04:40.490 --> 01:04:41.810 align:middle line:90%
Because it's technically--

01:04:41.810 --> 01:04:43.643 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Because
it's just like that.

01:04:43.643 --> 01:04:45.330 align:middle line:90%
These are non-negative number.

01:04:45.330 --> 01:04:48.010 align:middle line:84%
And that they are
summable just means

01:04:48.010 --> 01:04:52.470 align:middle line:84%
that if I go out really, really
far, then from there on out,

01:04:52.470 --> 01:04:55.890 align:middle line:84%
it makes very little
contribution to the total sum.

01:04:55.890 --> 01:04:58.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:58.570 --> 01:04:59.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:01.330 align:middle line:90%
So right.

01:05:01.330 --> 01:05:04.950 align:middle line:90%
So right.

01:05:04.950 --> 01:05:11.370 align:middle line:84%
So you see the first thing
is, for each fixed x,

01:05:11.370 --> 01:05:17.210 align:middle line:84%
I prove that these Sn of x is a
Cauchy sequence that then allow

01:05:17.210 --> 01:05:21.170 align:middle line:90%
me to define a function S of x.

01:05:21.170 --> 01:05:25.190 align:middle line:84%
And I get that the sequence
Sn of x is converging.

01:05:25.190 --> 01:05:27.810 align:middle line:84%
The sequence function
is converging pointwise.

01:05:27.810 --> 01:05:30.090 align:middle line:84%
And then again,
once I have that,

01:05:30.090 --> 01:05:33.450 align:middle line:84%
then I need to upgrade it
to be uniform convergence.

01:05:33.450 --> 01:05:35.290 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we did here.

01:05:35.290 --> 01:05:35.790 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:05:35.790 --> 01:05:38.670 align:middle line:90%


01:05:38.670 --> 01:05:39.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:39.750 --> 01:05:44.710 align:middle line:90%
So now let's try to apply this.

01:05:44.710 --> 01:05:45.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:05:45.870 --> 01:05:52.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So what if the Mk's
are kind of converging sequence

01:05:52.030 --> 01:05:58.070 align:middle line:84%
but in the small side, the
0 side, is on a low index?

01:05:58.070 --> 01:06:05.270 align:middle line:84%
So then, as I go further
out, it's getting bigger.

01:06:05.270 --> 01:06:07.090 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Can
we look at an example

01:06:07.090 --> 01:06:09.630 align:middle line:90%
and see if it becomes clear?

01:06:09.630 --> 01:06:13.275 align:middle line:90%
So let's look at a sort of--

01:06:13.275 --> 01:06:16.670 align:middle line:90%
let's look at an example.

01:06:16.670 --> 01:06:21.830 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at a very-- yeah,
let's look at an example.

01:06:21.830 --> 01:06:25.550 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, let's look at the
function, the example we just

01:06:25.550 --> 01:06:27.760 align:middle line:84%
looked at, where we
said that it followed

01:06:27.760 --> 01:06:30.820 align:middle line:90%
from Weierstrass M-test.

01:06:30.820 --> 01:06:34.600 align:middle line:84%
So what was the example
I just looked at?

01:06:34.600 --> 01:06:39.480 align:middle line:90%
So I take a function fn of x.

01:06:39.480 --> 01:06:46.360 align:middle line:84%
This is now x to the n
divided by n factorial.

01:06:46.360 --> 01:06:51.400 align:middle line:90%
Now I define Sn of x.

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:55.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is now the
sum from k equal to 0

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:57.960 align:middle line:90%
to n of this fn of x--

01:06:57.960 --> 01:06:59.680 align:middle line:90%
fk of x, sorry.

01:06:59.680 --> 01:07:02.080 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here

01:07:02.080 --> 01:07:10.440 align:middle line:84%
is the sum from k equal to 0
to n of xk over k factorial.

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:11.600 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:11.600 --> 01:07:14.720 align:middle line:90%
And I want to show that this--

01:07:14.720 --> 01:07:23.480 align:middle line:84%
so I want to show
that this Sn of x

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:34.930 align:middle line:84%
converges to the exponential
function uniformly

01:07:34.930 --> 01:07:39.370 align:middle line:90%
on an interval of this form.

01:07:39.370 --> 01:07:42.010 align:middle line:84%
So L is some fixed
number, and I'm

01:07:42.010 --> 01:07:45.950 align:middle line:84%
looking between minus L to L.
And I claim that they converge.

01:07:45.950 --> 01:07:49.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to apply
Weierstrass M-test.

01:07:49.230 --> 01:07:53.210 align:middle line:90%
And so what are the Mn?

01:07:53.210 --> 01:07:56.170 align:middle line:84%
The Mn, in this
case, the natural one

01:07:56.170 --> 01:08:01.670 align:middle line:84%
is L to the power n
times n factorial.

01:08:01.670 --> 01:08:04.622 align:middle line:90%


01:08:04.622 --> 01:08:10.730 align:middle line:84%
If I'm looking at those numbers,
these are non-negative numbers.

01:08:10.730 --> 01:08:16.490 align:middle line:84%
And we already know that this
sequence of non-negative numbers

01:08:16.490 --> 01:08:20.569 align:middle line:84%
is summable, that these
non-negative numbers,

01:08:20.569 --> 01:08:22.970 align:middle line:84%
like this, that
they are summable.

01:08:22.970 --> 01:08:29.670 align:middle line:90%


01:08:29.670 --> 01:08:32.109 align:middle line:90%
And suppose now I have--

01:08:32.109 --> 01:08:36.950 align:middle line:90%
suppose now I take this fn of x.

01:08:36.950 --> 01:08:41.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is this function x to
the power n over n factorial.

01:08:41.870 --> 01:08:46.830 align:middle line:84%
x here, remember, is in
this bounded interval.

01:08:46.830 --> 01:08:50.950 align:middle line:90%
Well, let's look at fn of x.

01:08:50.950 --> 01:08:56.470 align:middle line:90%
So this is xn over n factorial.

01:08:56.470 --> 01:08:58.470 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here--
so this is just

01:08:58.470 --> 01:09:02.710 align:middle line:90%
x to the power n n factorial.

01:09:02.710 --> 01:09:05.130 align:middle line:90%
This is why it's lying in here.

01:09:05.130 --> 01:09:08.710 align:middle line:84%
So the absolute value
is bounded by L.

01:09:08.710 --> 01:09:13.250 align:middle line:90%
So this is L n over n factorial.

01:09:13.250 --> 01:09:20.470 align:middle line:84%
So I have that this sequence
is less than this Mn.

01:09:20.470 --> 01:09:22.939 align:middle line:90%
And so now, Weierstrass.

01:09:22.939 --> 01:09:27.399 align:middle line:84%
But we restrict to
this interval here.

01:09:27.399 --> 01:09:34.840 align:middle line:84%
And so now Weierstrass M-test
tells you that the sum here,

01:09:34.840 --> 01:09:41.920 align:middle line:84%
when you're summing from k to
0 to n xk over k factorial,

01:09:41.920 --> 01:09:52.220 align:middle line:84%
that these actually converge
to the limit uniformly on--

01:09:52.220 --> 01:09:56.160 align:middle line:84%
But remember, we
are restricting.

01:09:56.160 --> 01:10:01.320 align:middle line:84%
And the limit here, we
already have defined the limit

01:10:01.320 --> 01:10:03.030 align:middle line:90%
to be the exponential function.

01:10:03.030 --> 01:10:08.290 align:middle line:90%


01:10:08.290 --> 01:10:10.200 align:middle line:90%
Is that clear or not?

01:10:10.200 --> 01:10:13.520 align:middle line:90%
Does that answer, or not really?

01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:14.880 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: I'm not sure.

01:10:14.880 --> 01:10:16.140 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK.

01:10:16.140 --> 01:10:19.070 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So I guess
my question was,

01:10:19.070 --> 01:10:23.465 align:middle line:84%
is it that Mn must be
a convergent series?

01:10:23.465 --> 01:10:24.340 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

01:10:24.340 --> 01:10:26.060 align:middle line:90%
So Mn-- that's right.

01:10:26.060 --> 01:10:28.620 align:middle line:90%
So Mn.

01:10:28.620 --> 01:10:34.385 align:middle line:84%
Mn, in this example or in
the general example, it's--

01:10:34.385 --> 01:10:37.180 align:middle line:90%


01:10:37.180 --> 01:10:40.440 align:middle line:84%
so why is the Mn so much
easier to determine?

01:10:40.440 --> 01:10:42.200 align:middle line:90%
Because they are just numbers.

01:10:42.200 --> 01:10:44.280 align:middle line:84%
They are just
non-negative numbers.

01:10:44.280 --> 01:10:48.980 align:middle line:84%
And you're just asking if the
series of non-negative numbers--

01:10:48.980 --> 01:10:51.340 align:middle line:84%
it's not function, it's
non-negative numbers--

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:53.160 align:middle line:90%
if that's convergent or not.

01:10:53.160 --> 01:10:56.740 align:middle line:84%
And so since they're
non-negative,

01:10:56.740 --> 01:11:01.145 align:middle line:84%
it just means that
the sum is finite.

01:11:01.145 --> 01:11:07.920 align:middle line:84%
And so that's much
easier to determine.

01:11:07.920 --> 01:11:08.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:08.420 --> 01:11:11.680 align:middle line:90%


01:11:11.680 --> 01:11:17.660 align:middle line:84%
So now we can do the same
argument more generally.

01:11:17.660 --> 01:11:26.790 align:middle line:84%
So this leads us to the
following, that suppose

01:11:26.790 --> 01:11:28.080 align:middle line:90%
you take a power series.

01:11:28.080 --> 01:11:33.750 align:middle line:90%


01:11:33.750 --> 01:11:36.030 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take
a power series.

01:11:36.030 --> 01:11:42.210 align:middle line:84%
So you're summing here n
equal to 0 to infinity a n xn.

01:11:42.210 --> 01:11:44.310 align:middle line:90%
This is a power series.

01:11:44.310 --> 01:11:45.370 align:middle line:90%
So power series.

01:11:45.370 --> 01:11:48.110 align:middle line:84%
Remember that a
power series is where

01:11:48.110 --> 01:11:53.070 align:middle line:84%
you're taking a sequence
of numbers, real numbers,

01:11:53.070 --> 01:11:56.630 align:middle line:84%
and you think about these as
coefficients in this polynomial.

01:11:56.630 --> 01:11:58.870 align:middle line:84%
And then you're
summing over them.

01:11:58.870 --> 01:12:07.350 align:middle line:84%
But it's like-- a n is the
coefficient to x to the power n.

01:12:07.350 --> 01:12:08.690 align:middle line:90%
So this is a power series.

01:12:08.690 --> 01:12:10.410 align:middle line:90%
And a power series again means--

01:12:10.410 --> 01:12:14.390 align:middle line:84%
so you think about it as a
series because for each x,

01:12:14.390 --> 01:12:16.970 align:middle line:90%
it's like a regular series.

01:12:16.970 --> 01:12:23.090 align:middle line:84%
But then it's like the value
that you get depends on x.

01:12:23.090 --> 01:12:26.990 align:middle line:84%
And so for this, we defined
the radius of convergence.

01:12:26.990 --> 01:12:34.610 align:middle line:90%


01:12:34.610 --> 01:12:38.930 align:middle line:84%
And let me remind you how
this radius of convergence

01:12:38.930 --> 01:12:41.090 align:middle line:90%
was defined.

01:12:41.090 --> 01:12:47.710 align:middle line:84%
You take the a n, and you
take the absolute value of it,

01:12:47.710 --> 01:12:50.650 align:middle line:84%
and then you take the
n-th root of that.

01:12:50.650 --> 01:12:56.150 align:middle line:84%
And then you're looking at
limsup as n goes to infinity.

01:12:56.150 --> 01:13:00.418 align:middle line:90%


01:13:00.418 --> 01:13:02.890 align:middle line:90%
That gives you some number.

01:13:02.890 --> 01:13:06.490 align:middle line:84%
That number potentially
could be infinity.

01:13:06.490 --> 01:13:09.990 align:middle line:84%
It's always non-negative, and it
will always give you a number.

01:13:09.990 --> 01:13:12.250 align:middle line:84%
It could be 0, it
could be infinity,

01:13:12.250 --> 01:13:15.010 align:middle line:84%
and it could be
anything in between.

01:13:15.010 --> 01:13:17.560 align:middle line:84%
And then the radius
of convergence--

01:13:17.560 --> 01:13:21.980 align:middle line:90%


01:13:21.980 --> 01:13:33.770 align:middle line:84%
of convergence of
the power series is--

01:13:33.770 --> 01:13:36.660 align:middle line:90%


01:13:36.660 --> 01:13:43.260 align:middle line:84%
so this is right by R.
And this is 1 over M.

01:13:43.260 --> 01:13:47.473 align:middle line:84%
And where this convention
in this case-- usually,

01:13:47.473 --> 01:13:51.240 align:middle line:84%
you don't divide
by 0 or infinity.

01:13:51.240 --> 01:13:54.560 align:middle line:84%
But in this case,
if M here is 0,

01:13:54.560 --> 01:13:58.180 align:middle line:84%
this means that the radius
of convergence is infinite.

01:13:58.180 --> 01:14:04.300 align:middle line:84%
If M is infinite, then it means
that the radius of convergence

01:14:04.300 --> 01:14:04.940 align:middle line:90%
is 0.

01:14:04.940 --> 01:14:10.000 align:middle line:84%
And now the slightly
surprising fact.

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:11.260 align:middle line:90%
But we proved this.

01:14:11.260 --> 01:14:13.860 align:middle line:84%
But I'm just reminding
you about it,

01:14:13.860 --> 01:14:22.710 align:middle line:84%
that the thing is that the
power series is convergent.

01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:24.230 align:middle line:90%
So here you have 0.

01:14:24.230 --> 01:14:27.090 align:middle line:90%
It's convergent inside.

01:14:27.090 --> 01:14:33.030 align:middle line:84%
If this here is R, it's
convergent inside here,

01:14:33.030 --> 01:14:35.670 align:middle line:90%
and it's divergent outside.

01:14:35.670 --> 01:14:40.782 align:middle line:84%
But it's not completely clear
what happened on the boundary.

01:14:40.782 --> 01:14:47.010 align:middle line:84%
So you have to check
the boundary separately.

01:14:47.010 --> 01:14:48.930 align:middle line:90%
And that depends on the power.

01:14:48.930 --> 01:14:52.110 align:middle line:84%
There's no general
formula for that.

01:14:52.110 --> 01:14:58.510 align:middle line:84%
So now the theorem
here is that--

01:14:58.510 --> 01:15:00.330 align:middle line:90%
so the theorem is like this.

01:15:00.330 --> 01:15:04.430 align:middle line:84%
And this is just generalizing
this example that we just did.

01:15:04.430 --> 01:15:07.990 align:middle line:84%
And the theorem
is the following,

01:15:07.990 --> 01:15:10.000 align:middle line:84%
that if you take
a power series--

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:13.430 align:middle line:90%


01:15:13.430 --> 01:15:24.810 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a
power series and R

01:15:24.810 --> 01:15:40.070 align:middle line:84%
is the radius of
convergence and L here,

01:15:40.070 --> 01:15:45.210 align:middle line:84%
it has to be strictly less
than the radius of convergence,

01:15:45.210 --> 01:15:55.530 align:middle line:84%
then these functions here,
k equal to 0 to n a n--

01:15:55.530 --> 01:16:01.250 align:middle line:84%
ak sorry, xk, that
these functions here

01:16:01.250 --> 01:16:27.400 align:middle line:84%
converge to the limit here
uniformly on this interval here,

01:16:27.400 --> 01:16:29.260 align:middle line:90%
from minus L to L.

01:16:29.260 --> 01:16:32.460 align:middle line:84%
Remember that L had
to be strictly less

01:16:32.460 --> 01:16:36.836 align:middle line:90%
than the radius of convergence.

01:16:36.836 --> 01:16:39.660 align:middle line:90%
And so this is extremely useful.

01:16:39.660 --> 01:16:45.940 align:middle line:84%
If you have-- and it will be
clear next time why it's useful

01:16:45.940 --> 01:16:48.940 align:middle line:84%
because if you have
uniform convergence,

01:16:48.940 --> 01:16:51.580 align:middle line:90%
then it becomes very easy--

01:16:51.580 --> 01:16:53.660 align:middle line:84%
if you have uniform
convergence, then you

01:16:53.660 --> 01:16:56.620 align:middle line:84%
can argue about if
you want to take

01:16:56.620 --> 01:17:00.220 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of integrating
this thing over here,

01:17:00.220 --> 01:17:03.540 align:middle line:84%
if you have uniform
convergence, then

01:17:03.540 --> 01:17:08.100 align:middle line:84%
it will say that then
a lot of operations

01:17:08.100 --> 01:17:10.480 align:middle line:84%
will be more precise
about that next time.

01:17:10.480 --> 01:17:14.880 align:middle line:84%
But a lot of operations, like
integration and differentiation,

01:17:14.880 --> 01:17:19.580 align:middle line:84%
you can do that over here
and then go to the limit.

01:17:19.580 --> 01:17:24.520 align:middle line:84%
So instead of if you were to
integrate this thing here.

01:17:24.520 --> 01:17:29.120 align:middle line:84%
So just say that-- but this
seems maybe very, very hard.

01:17:29.120 --> 01:17:31.720 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is, if
you can integrate here,

01:17:31.720 --> 01:17:34.360 align:middle line:84%
then you can just
use the usual sum,

01:17:34.360 --> 01:17:36.720 align:middle line:90%
the usual formula for the sum.

01:17:36.720 --> 01:17:38.760 align:middle line:84%
It's just the sum
of the integral.

01:17:38.760 --> 01:17:42.680 align:middle line:84%
And likewise for
differentiation.

01:17:42.680 --> 01:17:45.510 align:middle line:90%
And so, OK, maybe I will just--

01:17:45.510 --> 01:17:48.420 align:middle line:90%


01:17:48.420 --> 01:17:48.920 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:17:48.920 --> 01:17:50.760 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I'll just stop here.

01:17:50.760 --> 01:17:55.480 align:middle line:84%
I wrote out the
proof in the notes.

01:17:55.480 --> 01:17:59.080 align:middle line:84%
And I already posted the
notes, the lecture notes.

01:17:59.080 --> 01:18:00.720 align:middle line:90%
Are there any questions?

01:18:00.720 --> 01:18:05.560 align:middle line:90%


01:18:05.560 --> 01:18:06.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:06.320 --> 01:18:07.870 align:middle line:90%
Great.

01:18:07.870 --> 01:18:11.000 align:middle line:90%